[[Image:Daianji Hondo01.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Daian-ji [[Main Hall (Japanese Buddhism)|Hondō]]]]
[[File:South Gate of Daianji 20150404.jpg|thumb|right|300px|South gate]]

{{nihongo|'''Daian-ji'''|大安寺}} was founded during the [[Asuka period]] and is one of the [[Nanto Shichi Daiji|Seven Great Temples]] of [[Nara, Nara|Nara]], [[Japan]].

==History==
The [[Nihon Shoki]] records the founding of the {{nihongo|Kudara Dai-ji|百済大寺}}, predecessor of the Daian-ji, in 639 during the reign of [[Emperor Jomei]]. A nine-story pagoda was added shortly afterwards.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Four Great Temples (''vid.'' pp. 90, 83–153) |author=McCallum, Donald F. |publisher=[[University of Hawaii Press]] |year=2009 |ISBN=978-0-8248-3114-1}}</ref> Moved during the reign of [[Emperor Tenmu]], excavations have uncovered the foundations of the site of the {{nihongo|Daikandai-ji|大官大寺}}, as it was then known, seven hundred metres to the south of Mount Kagu.<ref>{{cite  web |url=http://www.daianji.or.jp/02-garan.html |title=Temple |publisher=Daian-ji |accessdate=28 March 2011}}</ref> Like the [[Yakushi-ji]], and [[Gangō-ji]], the temple relocated to the new capital of [[Heijō-kyō]] in 716–17, and it was rebuilt as the Daian-ji in 729.<ref name="Heibonsha">{{cite book |title=Temples of Nara and their Art (''vid.'' pp. 33 f.) |author=Ooka, Minoru |publisher=[[Weatherhill]] |year=1973 |ISBN=0-8348-1010-7}}</ref> Its importance declined when the capital moved again to [[Kyoto]] at the end of the [[Nara period]]. A succession of fires, a typhoon in 1459 and earthquakes in 1585 and 1596 destroyed most of the temple.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.daianji.or.jp/03-reki.html |title=History |publisher=Daian-ji |accessdate=28 March 2011}}</ref> The stone bases of the former twin pagodas were removed for reuse at [[Kashihara Shrine|Kashihara Jingū]] in 1889,<ref>{{cite book |title=Early Buddhist Japan (''vid.'' p. 114) |author=Kidder, J. Edward |publisher=[[Thames and Hudson]] |year=1972 |ISBN=0-500-02078-7}}</ref> while the ruins of the other buildings lie in adjacent properties.<ref name="Heibonsha"/>

==Treasures==
The temple houses nine statues in a style known as Daianji-yoshiki, but the acclaimed statue of [[Sakyamuni]], said by the twelfth-century Oe no Chikamichi in ''[[Nanto Shichi Daiji|Shichidaiji]] [[Junrei]] Shiki'' to have been the finest work in Nara, is now lost.<ref name="Heibonsha"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pref.nara.jp/nara_e/dd_aspx_menuid-1260.htm |title=Daianji Temple |publisher=[[Nara Prefecture]] |accessdate=28 March 2011}}</ref> The following [[Nara period]] statues have been designated [[Important Cultural Properties of Japan|Important Cultural Properties]]: a [[Jūichimen Kannon]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=201&item_id=4068 |title=Database of Registered National Cultural Properties |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=27 March 2011}}</ref> [[Kannon|Senjū Kannon]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=201&item_id=4064 |title=Database of Registered National Cultural Properties |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=27 March 2011}}</ref> [[Kannon|Fukūkensaku Kannon]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=201&item_id=4065 |title=Database of Registered National Cultural Properties |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=27 March 2011}}</ref> [[Kannon|Yōryū Kannon]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=201&item_id=4066 |title=Database of Registered National Cultural Properties |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=27 March 2011}}</ref> [[Kannon|Shō Kannon]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=201&item_id=4069 |title=Database of Registered National Cultural Properties |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=27 March 2011}}</ref>  and a set of [[Four Heavenly Kings]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=201&item_id=4067 |title=Database of Registered National Cultural Properties |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=27 March 2011}}</ref> Temple records of the [[Tenpyō]] era (747) have also been designated an [[Important Cultural Properties of Japan|Important Cultural Property]] and are now held in [[Chiba Prefecture]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=201&item_id=9161 |title=Database of Registered National Cultural Properties |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=27 March 2011}}</ref>

