'''Theological hermeneutics''' is a field of [[theology]]. It broadly refers to the application of [[hermeneutics]] with theological means to theological texts,<ref>{{cite book|last=Jeanrond|first=Werner G.|title=Theological hermeneutics: development and significance|year=1994|publisher=SCM Press|isbn=978-0-334-01624-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2atzQgAACAAJ&dq=%22Theological+hermeneutics%22&hl=en&ei=OslNTLuvPIG88gai24GaDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAQ}}</ref> particularly [[scripture]].<ref>''Theological Hermeneutics'', p. 86, Alexander S. Jensen, SCM 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-334-02901-4}}</ref> Theological hermeneutics dated from [[Philo]] and [[Origen]]<ref>(1999)Dictionary of Biblical Interpretation, D.E. Klemm, "Hermeneutics", 497-502</ref>, and [[Protestant Reformers|Reformers]] like [[Martin Luther]] using the distinction between the Law<ref>[http://lighthouselutheran.s3.amazonaws.com/Papers/Lutheran%20Understanding%20of%20Law%20and%20Gospel.pdf Dennis Whalen, Lutheran Understanding of Law and Gospe]</ref> and the Gospel and [[John Calvin]] using the ideal of ''brevitas et facilitas''<ref>[https://repository.up.ac.za/bitstream/handle/2263/20883/Ahn_Ideal%281999%29.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y Ahn, Myung Jun, The Ideal of ''Brevitas et Facilitas'': the theological hermeneutics of John Calvin, Skrif en Kerk Volume 20 Issue 2 (1999)]</ref> <ref>[https://repository.up.ac.za/handle/2263/26944 Ahn, Myung Jun, Brevitas et facilitas : a study of a vital aspect in the theological hermeneutics of John Calvin (Ph.D. Diss., University of Pretoria, 1998)]</ref>

==Christian hermeneutics==
{{Main|Biblical hermeneutics}}

'''Biblical hermeneutics''' is the study of the principles of interpretation concerning the books of the [[Bible]]. It is part of the broader field of [[hermeneutics]] which involves the study of principles for the text and includes all forms of communication: verbal and nonverbal.<ref>{{Cite book
